---
import BaseLayout from "../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import EditorialNote from "../../components/EditorialNote.astro";
import RelatedLinks from "../../components/RelatedLinks.astro";
import { appliances } from "../../data/appliances";
import { guides } from "../../data/guides";

const title = "Standby Power Cost: Calculate Idle and Vampire Energy Use";
const description = "Calculate the monthly and yearly cost of standby power from TVs, computers, chargers, kitchen devices, and other equipment left plugged in.";
const calculatorSlugs = ["tv-electricity-cost-calculator", "desktop-computer-electricity-cost-calculator", "laptop-electricity-cost-calculator", "gaming-pc-electricity-cost-calculator"];
const calculatorLinks = appliances.filter((item) => calculatorSlugs.includes(item.slug)).map((item) => ({
  eyebrow: item.category, title: `${item.name} Cost Calculator`, description: "Compare active use before adding standby separately.", href: `/calculators/${item.slug}/`,
}));
const guideLinks = guides.filter((guide) => ["how-to-measure-appliance-electricity-use", "how-to-calculate-electricity-cost", "appliance-energy-saving-tips"].includes(guide.slug)).map((guide) => ({
  eyebrow: guide.category, title: guide.title, description: guide.description, href: `/guides/${guide.slug}/`,
}));
const sources = [
  { title: "Standby Power", publisher: "Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory", url: "https://standby.lbl.gov/" },
  { title: "Estimating Appliance and Home Electronic Energy Use", publisher: "U.S. Department of Energy", url: "https://www.energy.gov/energysaver/estimating-appliance-and-home-electronic-energy-use" },
];
const articleSchema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org", "@type": "Article", headline: "Standby Power Cost Guide", description,
  dateModified: "2026-06-21", author: { "@type": "Organization", name: "WattCostGuide" },
  publisher: { "@type": "Organization", name: "WattCostGuide" },
  mainEntityOfPage: "https://wattcostguide.com/guides/standby-power-cost/", citation: sources.map((source) => source.url),
};
---

<BaseLayout title={title} description={description}>
  <nav class="breadcrumbs" aria-label="Breadcrumb"><a href="/">Home</a><span>/</span><a href="/guides/">Guides</a></nav>
  <section class="page-header">
    <p class="eyebrow">Electronics</p>
    <h1>Standby Power Cost Guide</h1>
    <p>Standby power is the electricity a device uses while it is not performing its main job but remains ready, connected, displaying information, or communicating.</p>
  </section>
  <EditorialNote updated="June 21, 2026" note="Standby draw varies by model and operating state. Measure the exact device before deciding whether an automation or smart plug will save energy." />

  <section class="section article-block">
    <h2>How to calculate standby cost</h2>
    <p>
      Standby wattage is usually small, but idle hours can be long. Estimate the hours per day that the device is
      in that state, then use the standard watts-to-kWh formula. Calculate active use separately so the two states
      are not counted at the same time.
    </p>
    <pre><code>Standby cost = Standby watts / 1000 x Standby hours x Electricity rate</code></pre>
    <p>At $0.18 per kWh, a continuous 5W standby load costs about $0.66 per month or $7.88 per year.</p>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <h2>Example standby costs at $0.18 per kWh</h2>
    <div class="table-wrap"><table>
      <thead><tr><th>Continuous standby load</th><th>Monthly energy</th><th>Monthly cost</th><th>Yearly cost</th></tr></thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td>1W</td><td>0.72 kWh</td><td>$0.13</td><td>$1.58</td></tr>
        <tr><td>5W</td><td>3.60 kWh</td><td>$0.65</td><td>$7.88</td></tr>
        <tr><td>10W</td><td>7.20 kWh</td><td>$1.30</td><td>$15.77</td></tr>
        <tr><td>25W</td><td>18.00 kWh</td><td>$3.24</td><td>$39.42</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table></div>
    <p class="lede">These examples assume the listed load continues for 24 hours every day. Subtract active-use hours when a device has already been counted in another operating state.</p>
  </section>

  <section class="section article-block">
    <h2>Off, standby, idle, and sleep are different states</h2>
    <p>
      A television waiting for a remote command is in standby. A computer that is awake but doing little is idle
      and usually draws more. Sleep mode saves system state while reducing power, but network wake features and
      connected accessories can remain active. A charger with no device attached may have a very small no-load
      draw, while a dock powering peripherals can use more.
    </p>
    <p>
      Label each measured state instead of describing everything as “off.” This makes the result repeatable and
      shows whether changing a setting is more useful than disconnecting the device.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="section-heading"><h2>Where to look first</h2><p>Prioritize groups of equipment and devices with network, display, or quick-start features.</p></div>
    <div class="insight-grid">
      <article class="insight-panel"><h3>Entertainment center</h3><p>Measure the TV, receiver, console, streaming box, soundbar, subwoofer, and powered antenna separately or as one switched group.</p></article>
      <article class="insight-panel"><h3>Computer workspace</h3><p>Include monitors, docks, speakers, printers, external drives, and network equipment. Confirm that sleep settings actually activate.</p></article>
      <article class="insight-panel"><h3>Kitchen controls</h3><p>Microwaves, coffee makers, and ranges may power clocks or network features. Their standby draw is separate from short high-power heating periods.</p></article>
      <article class="insight-panel"><h3>Always-needed equipment</h3><p>Routers, security systems, medical equipment, refrigerators, and essential controls should not be disconnected merely to remove standby consumption.</p></article>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section article-block">
    <h2>How to measure a low standby load</h2>
    <p>
      Use an energy meter that can resolve low wattage. Let the device finish updates, charging, or cool-down before
      recording its settled state. If an instant reading fluctuates or rounds to zero, accumulate energy for a day
      or longer and divide by elapsed hours to find average watts.
    </p>
    <pre><code>Average standby watts = Measured kWh x 1000 / Hours measured</code></pre>
    <p>
      For a collection of devices on one power strip, first measure the whole strip, then disconnect one device at
      a time if you need to identify the largest contributor.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="section article-block">
    <h2>When switching power off makes sense</h2>
    <p>
      A switched power strip can help when several nonessential devices share the same usage schedule. Smart plugs
      can automate a schedule, but the plug also consumes power, so compare its own draw with the load it controls.
      Built-in sleep, eco, auto-off, and quick-start settings are often simpler and preserve normal operation.
    </p>
    <p>
      Avoid cutting power to equipment that requires continuous operation, safe shutdown, remote access, scheduled
      updates, temperature control, or medical reliability. Check manufacturer instructions before switching a load.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="section faq-list">
    <h2>Standby power FAQ</h2>
    <details open><summary>Do phone chargers use electricity when no phone is connected?</summary><p>Many have a small no-load draw, but the amount varies and can be difficult to resolve on a basic meter. Measure the charger or use reliable model information before estimating savings.</p></details>
    <details><summary>Is sleep mode the same as turning a computer off?</summary><p>No. Sleep normally uses much less than an awake computer but may still power memory, wake features, docks, or accessories. Shutdown can also retain a small standby load.</p></details>
    <details><summary>Should I unplug every device?</summary><p>No. Start with measured, nonessential loads that stay idle for long periods. Safety, convenience, equipment requirements, and the energy used by switching devices should be considered.</p></details>
  </section>

  <section class="section article-block" aria-labelledby="sources-heading">
    <div class="section-heading"><h2 id="sources-heading">Sources</h2><p>Research and government guidance for standby and appliance energy measurement.</p></div>
    <ul class="source-list">{sources.map((source) => <li><a href={source.url}>{source.title}</a><span>{source.publisher}</span></li>)}</ul>
  </section>
  <RelatedLinks title="Compare active electronics use" description="Estimate active cost first, then add measured standby as a separate operating state." links={calculatorLinks} />
  <RelatedLinks title="Related electricity guides" description="Measure low loads, use the cost formula, and choose practical savings actions." links={guideLinks} />
  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify(articleSchema)} />
</BaseLayout>
